definition.value: An oxo dicarboxylic acid that consists of glutaric acid bearing an oxo substituent at position 2. It is an intermediate metabolite in Krebs cycle.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion resulting from selective deprotonation of the 1-carboxy group of 2-oxoglutaric acid.
A tartaric acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-carboxy-2,3-dihydroxypropanoate.
A dideoxyhexose that is L-arabinohexose in which the hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 6 are replaced by hydrogen.
A potassium salt which is the monopotassium salt of thiocyanic acid.
A C28, very long straight-chain, saturated fatty acid.
A very long straight-chain saturated fatty acid anion and the conjugate base of octacosanoic acid (montanic acid), arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A C30, very long straight-chain, saturated fatty acid.
A very long straight-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of melissic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.
A straight-chain alkane with 30 carbon atoms.
A 26-carbon, straight-chain, saturated fatty acid.
A short-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of valeric acid; present in ester form as component of many steroid-based pharmaceuticals.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of lignoceric acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The (13S)-diastereomer of 13-dihydrodaunorubicin.

An aminoglycoside antibiotic that is (1S,3S)-3-ethyl-3,5,12-trihydroxy-10-methoxy-6,11-dioxo-1,2,3,4,6,11-hexahydrotetracene having a 3-amino-2,3,6-trideoxy-alpha-L-lyxo-hexopyranosyl residue attached at position 1 via a glycosidic linkage.

An aminoglycoside antibiotic that is (1S,3S)-3,5,12-trihydroxy-3-(1-hydroxyethyl)-10-methoxy-6,11-dioxo-1,2,3,4,6,11-hexahydrotetracene having a 3-amino-2,3,6-trideoxy-alpha-L-lyxo-hexopyranosyl residue attached at position 1 via a glycosidic linkage.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is hexanedioic acid containing a double bond between positions 2 and 3, an oxo group at position 4, and two chlorine atoms (at positions 2 and 5).
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is 4-hydroxybenzoic acid bearing an additional dimethylallyl substituent at position 3.

A carboxylic ester that is the carboxymethyl ester of indometacin. A non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, it is used in the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis, osteoarthritis, and low back pain, as well as for postoperative pain and inflammation. Its activity is due to both acemetacin and its major metabolite, indometacin.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate of the sodium salt of amfenac.
An inorganic chloride having ammonium as the counterion.
A glycerol phosphate that consists of a linear array of three glycerol units connected by phosphodiester linkages.
A  pyrazolone derivative that is 1,2-dihydropyrazol-3-one substituted with methyl groups at C-1 and C-5 and with a phenyl group at N-2.

The hydrochloride salt of butenafine. An inhibitor of squalene epoxidase, an enzyme responsible for the creation of sterols needed in fungal cell membranes, it is used for treatment of dermatological fungal infections.
An organic calcium salt having glycerol 2-phosphate(2-) as the counterion.

A carbamate ester that is cytidine in which the hydrogen at position 5 is replaced by fluorine and in which the amino group attached to position 4 is converted to its N-(penyloxy)carbonyl derivative. Capecitabine is a antineoplastic agent used in the treatment of cancers.
A toxic anthracycline antibiotic that is produced by Actinomadura carminata and also has potent antineoplastic activity.
A carotenoic acid that is the 6'-monomethyl ester of 9'-cis-6,6'-diapocarotene-6,6'-dioic acid.
A hydrochloride that is the monohydrate of the dihydrochloride salt of cefepime.
